<subSubSection pageId="155" pageNumber="434" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="155.[770,1361,1081,1508]" lastBlockId="155.[157,1362,1514,2218]" pageId="155" pageNumber="434">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[771,1029,1356,1389]" pageId="155" pageNumber="434">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 104 mm, tail 149 mm, ear (dry) 16 mm, hindfoot 26 mm (holotype). No specific data are available for body weight. The Andean Pygmy Rice Rat is a medium-sized species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bangs" authorityYear="1900" box="[805,968,1514,1547]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Oligoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="155" pageNumber="434" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Oligoryzomys</taxonomicName>
, similar to Tschudi’s Pygmy Rice Rat (
<taxonomicName box="[305,473,1554,1587]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Hesperomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="155" pageNumber="434" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="destructor">O. destructor</taxonomicName>
) but with longer hindfeet and very long tail. Dorsum is pale ocherous, darkened by numerous fine dusky lines; slight ocherous lateral line is present; face and head are somewhat grayish; and underparts are creamy white and sharply differentiated, and hairs have slaty bases. Ears are thinly haired, ocherous basally and internally, and brownish distally and externally. Dorsal surfaces of forefeet and hindfeet are white. Tail is thinly covered with very short hair, brownish above, whitish below for proximal one-half, and gradually dusky toward tip. Chromosomal complement is 2n = 60, FN = 70.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="155" pageNumber="434" type="biology_ecology">
